Exercise 1: MIIV Search

Load MIIVsem

library(MIIVsem)

Rename data to match slides

data <- bollen1989a
colnames(data) <- c(paste0("Z",4:11), paste0("Z",1:3))

Specify industrialization-democracy model

model.indem1 <- '
  L1 =~ Z1 + Z2 + Z3 
  L2 =~ Z4 + Z5 + Z6  + Z7  
  L3 =~ Z8 + Z9 + Z10 + Z11    
  L2  ~ L1  
  L3  ~ L1 + L2
  Z4 ~~ Z8
  Z5 ~~ Z7 + Z9
  Z6 ~~ Z10
  Z7 ~~ Z11
  Z9 ~~ Z11 
'

Run MIIV search

miivs(model.indem1)
## Model Equation Information 
## 
##  LHS RHS    MIIVs

##  Z5  Z4     Z6, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z10, Z11

##  Z7  Z4     Z6, Z9, Z1, Z2, Z3, Z10

Compare SEs for Standard Bootstrap with Different Numbers of Replications

fit.standard  <- miive(model.indem1, data)
fit.boot.250  <- miive(model.indem1, data, se = "boot", bootstrap = 250)
fit.boot.500  <- miive(model.indem1, data, se = "boot", bootstrap = 500)
fit.boot.1000 <- miive(model.indem1, data, se = "boot", bootstrap = 1000)

est.standard  <- estimatesTable(fit.standard)[,c("lhs", "op", "rhs", "se")]
est.boot.250  <- estimatesTable(fit.boot.250)[,c("lhs", "op", "rhs", "se")] 
est.boot.500  <- estimatesTable(fit.boot.500)[,c("lhs", "op", "rhs", "se")] 
est.boot.1000 <- estimatesTable(fit.boot.1000)[,c("lhs", "op", "rhs", "se")] 

list.est <- list(est.standard,est.boot.250,est.boot.500, est.boot.1000)
compare.se <- Reduce(function(...) merge(..., by= c("lhs", "op", "rhs")), list.est)

colnames(compare.se) <- c("", "", "", "standard", "boot.250", "boot.500", "boot.1000")

Exercise 5: Measurement Model Robustness to Latent Variable Model Misspecification

Load lavaan

library(lavaan)

Correct and Misspecified Model

  • Latent variable model is correct (solid and dashed lines)
  • Latent variable model is incorrect (omitting dashed lines)

Specify Data Generating Model

model.sim.1 <- '
  
  L1  =~ 1*Z1  + 1*Z2  + 1*Z3
  L2  =~ 1*Z13 + 1*Z14 + 1*Z15
  L3  =~ 1*Z4  + 1*Z5  + 1*Z6
  L4  =~ 1*Z7  + 1*Z8  + 1*Z9
  L5  =~ 1*Z10 + 1*Z11 + 1*Z12
  
  L3 ~  .3*L1 + .5*L4
  L4 ~  .5*L2 + .8*L3
  L5 ~  .3*L2 + .5*L4

  L3 ~~ .6*L4
'

Simulate data

  • Simulated data to true model
  • 1,000 observations
data.sim.1 <- simulateData(model = model.sim.1, 
                           sample.nobs = 1000, 
                           seed = 123)

Specify estimating models

model.correct.1 <- '
  
  L1  =~ Z1  + Z2  + Z3
  L2  =~ Z13 + Z14 + Z15
  L3  =~ Z4  + Z5  + Z6
  L4  =~ Z7  + Z8  + Z9
  L5  =~ Z10 + Z11 + Z12
  
  L3 ~  L1 + L4
  L4 ~  L2 + L3
  L5 ~  L2 + L4

  L3 ~~ L4

'

model.misspecified.1 <- '
  L1  =~ Z1  + Z2  + Z3
  L2  =~ Z13 + Z14 + Z15
  L3  =~ Z4  + Z5  + Z6
  L4  =~ Z7  + Z8  + Z9
  L5  =~ Z10 + Z11 + Z12

  L3 ~  L1 
  L4 ~  L3
  L5 ~  L4
'

Compare Estimates from Estimating Models

  fit.cor.1 <- miive(model.correct.1, data.sim.1)
  fit.mis.1 <- miive(model.misspecified.1, data.sim.1)
 
  est.cor.1 <- estimatesTable(fit.cor.1)
  est.mis.1 <- estimatesTable(fit.mis.1)
  
  compare.1 <- merge(
    est.cor.1[est.cor.1$op == "=~", c("lhs","op","rhs","est")],
    est.mis.1[est.mis.1$op == "=~", c("lhs","op","rhs","est")],
    by = c("lhs","op","rhs")
  )
  colnames(compare.1) <- c("","","","est.cor.1","est.mis.1")
  
  compare.1

Exercise 6: Latent Variable Robustness to Measurement Model Misspecification

Correct and Misspecified Model

  • Measurement model is correct (solid and dashed lines)
  • Measurement model is incorrect (omitting dashed lines)

Specify Data Generating Model

model.sim.2 <- '
  
  L1  =~ 1*Z1  + 1*Z2  + 1*Z3 + 1*Z5
  L2  =~ 1*Z4  + 1*Z5  + 1*Z6 + 1*Z8
  L3  =~ 1*Z7  + 1*Z8  + 1*Z9 

  L2  ~  1*L1
  L3  ~  1*L2

  Z2 ~~ .3*Z5
  Z6 ~~ .3*Z9
'

Simulate data

  • Simulated data to true model
  • 1,000 observations
data.sim.2 <- simulateData(model = model.sim.2, 
                           sample.nobs = 1000, 
                           seed = 123)

Specify estimating models

model.correct.2 <- '

  L1  =~ Z1  + Z2  + Z3 + Z5
  L2  =~ Z4  + Z5  + Z6 + Z8
  L3  =~ Z7  + Z8  + Z9 

  L2  ~  L1
  L3  ~  L2

  Z2 ~~ Z5
  Z6 ~~ Z9
'

model.misspecified.2 <- '

  L1  =~ Z1  + Z2  + Z3 
  L2  =~ Z4  + Z5  + Z6
  L3  =~ Z7  + Z8  + Z9 

  L2 ~  L1
  L3 ~  L2
'

Correctly Specified Model (Unadjusted Sargan)

Exercise 6: Latent Variable Robustness to Measurement Model Misspecification 2

Correct and Misspecified Model

  • Measurement model is correct (solid and dashed lines)
  • Measurement model is incorrect (omitting dashed lines)

Specify Data Generating Model

model.sim.3 <- '
  
  L1  =~ 1*Z1  + 1*Z2  + 1*Z3 + 1*Z5
  L2  =~ 1*Z4  + 1*Z5  + 1*Z6 
  L3  =~ 1*Z7  + 1*Z8  + 1*Z9 + 1*Z6 

  L2  ~  1*L1
  L3  ~  1*L2

  Z2 ~~ .3*Z5
  Z6 ~~ .3*Z9
'

Simulate data

  • Simulated data to true model
  • 1,000 observations
data.sim.3 <- simulateData(model = model.sim.3, 
                           sample.nobs = 1000, 
                           seed = 123)

Specify estimating models

model.correct.3 <- '

  L1  =~ Z1  + Z2  + Z3 + Z5
  L2  =~ Z4  + Z5  + Z6 
  L3  =~ Z7  + Z8  + Z9 + Z6

  L2  ~  L1
  L3  ~  L2

  Z2 ~~ Z5
  Z6 ~~ Z9
'

model.misspecified.3 <- '

  L1  =~ Z1  + Z2  + Z3 
  L2  =~ Z4  + Z5  + Z6

  L2 ~  L1
  L3 ~  L2
'

Exercise 7: Dimensionality Example

Data comes from a survey conducted in rural clusters of Tanzania (Bollen, 1996). The goal was to collect information on the perceived accessibility of a specific family planning facility that serviced each cluster.

Six informants were chosen: 3 female and 3 male. New informants were chosen for each cluster. Each informant was independently asked to rate the accessibility of the facility. More specifically the women informants were asked to rate how women of childbearing age perceived the accessibility of the clinic and the men informants were asked to rate how accessible men perceived the clinic to be.

The female informants’ ratings are access1-3 and the male informants’ ratings are access4-6.

Model 1

Using MIIVsem fit a confirmatory factor analysis model with a single accessibility latent variable underlying the six measures. The dataset is packaged with MIIVsem and named bollen1996.

The informants change from cluster to cluster. The ordering of the informants is arbitrary, this suggests the factor loadings for the informants might be equal, constrain all the loadings to equality.

Use access1 as the scaling indicator.

To specify equality constraints on parameters in the model syntax use labels prepended to the variable name using the * operator. For numeric constrains specify a number instead.

model.1 <- '
  accessibility =~  1*access1 + 1*access2 + 1*access3 +
                    1*access4 + 1*access5 + 1*access6
'

MIIVsem also includes an option to estimate test statistics for a large-sample Wald test of linear hypotheses imposed on the MIIV-2SLS coefficient matrix. The \(F\) and \(\chi^2\) are equivalent asymptotically but their performance may differ in small samples. Assumptions and additional details for each test are given by Greene (2003, pp. 346-347). The conduct the Wald test save the miive object and using the summary() method request restrict.tests=TRUE.

fit <- miive(model.1, bollen1996, sarg.adjust = "holm")

summary(fit, restrict.tests = TRUE)

Exercise 8: Polychoric Instrumental Variable Estimator

Following the convention used in lavaan, we use the ordered argument to indicate which variables in the model syntax are categorical. This will be demonstrated in the following example.

In our previous Accessibility example, responses were recorded on a 1-5 scale. We will reestimate our final two-factor model to demonstrate the PIV estimator.

model.piv <- '
  femaleAccess =~  access1 + access2 + access3
  maleAccess   =~  access4 + access5 + access6
'
